    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 8 @ 2021/2022",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A battery of emf 12V and internal resistance 2Ω is connected to a resistor of 16Ω. Which is the potential difference of the battery?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "21.33V",
        "10.667V",
        "0.75V",
        "24V"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "10.667V"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "The potential difference across the battery terminals (terminal voltage) is \\( V = \\text{EMF} - I r \\), where \\( I \\) is the current and \\( r \\) is the internal resistance. First, calculate the current using the total resistance: \\( R_{\\text{total}} = R_{\\text{external}} + r = 16 + 2 = 18 \\Omega \\). Current \\( I = \\frac{\\text{EMF}}{R_{\\text{total}}} = \\frac{12}{18} = \\frac{2}{3} \\text{A} \\). The voltage drop across the internal resistance is \\( I r = \\frac{2}{3} \\times 2 = \\frac{4}{3} \\text{V} \\). So, the terminal voltage is \\( V = 12 - \\frac{4}{3} = \\frac{36}{3} - \\frac{4}{3} = \\frac{32}{3} \\approx 10.667 \\text{V} \\). This makes 10.667V the correct answer. 21.33V and 24V are too high (exceeding the EMF), and 0.75V is too low (misinterpreting the circuit)."
    },
