  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 10 @ 2021/2022",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The potential difference between the terminals of a source when no current flows to an external circuit is called the",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "net voltage",
        "battery voltage",
        "electromotive force",
        "equivalent voltage"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "electromotive force"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "The potential difference across the terminals of a source when no current flows (open circuit) is called the electromotive force (EMF), which is why electromotive force is the correct answer. EMF is the maximum voltage a source can provide, measured when no current flows, so no energy is lost to internal resistance. Net voltage and battery voltage are not standard terms in this context. Equivalent voltage might refer to a combined circuit’s voltage, not the source’s EMF. Thus, electromotive force is the precise term."
    },
    "topic": [
